5pmDEq7gqalHlD8eyYB24Po1uH5m7NEjzm4-fiCOVp9AsFhqmysULrsy3h6FJOCTG1bIQRVJhehfhx9u5mPdoitW6zxe8CBGdOagTc=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating metadata needs**\\n\\nI’m assessing the test resources and considering whether to add metadata for T4CDriverExtension to improve reachability. It seems there’s no current metadata for it, which can lead to issues if a native failure happens. I'll think about adding a condition for OracleDriver, but the constructors aren't public. Since the library relies on reflection, having the correct metadata feels essential. However, the focus should really be on the user’s request about coverage, not just metadata.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Addressing native failures and tests**\\n\\nI’m considering adding metadata to the tests if a native failure occurs. In this repository, the tests pull library metadata during native execution, and we need to update the main metadata. There may be a need for an inspection since the OracleDriver class has a subclass but can use the active class directly, which is public. For testing connectivity, I should set a timeout using JUnit's @Timeout to ensure tests complete within 60 seconds and handle potential hangs in connection attempts. Parsing the connection URL sounds feasible too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying connection timeout and exceptions**\\n\\nIt seems that the ORACLE_NET.CONNECT_TIMEOUT property should probably be set to \\\"1000\\\" milliseconds. I'll need to assert that any SQLException that arises could be an SQLRecoverableException, which involves checking the getDriverExtension first. If Class.newInstance fails due to missing native metadata, catching that wouldn't help, so fixing the metadata is essential. I should ensure that any resulting exceptions clearly mention this issue. It sounds like clarity in exception handling will be important for debugging!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_h0EGxl7VaO52h0N8mq6Xie1P|